              "safetyPreview": "Chest pain, trouble swallowing, vomiting blood, black stool, weight loss, or persistent/worsening reflux needs medical evaluation."
          },
          "biologyPathway": [
              {
                  "title": "Pressure Builds",
                  "short": "Stomach pressure rises.",
                  "detail": "Large meals, lying down soon after eating, certain triggers, abdominal pressure, hiatal hernia, pregnancy, some medications, and stress-related tension can all increase reflux pressure."
              },
              {
                  "title": "LES Barrier Weakens",
                  "short": "The reflux valve does not hold fully.",
                  "detail": "The lower esophageal sphincter normally helps keep stomach contents down. When the barrier is weak or overwhelmed by pressure, acid and stomach contents can move upward."
              },
              {
                  "title": "Acid Exposure",
                  "short": "Stomach contents irritate the esophagus.",
                  "detail": "The esophagus is not built to handle repeated acid exposure. This can create burning, sour taste, regurgitation, throat irritation, cough, or hoarseness."
              },
              {
                  "title": "Symptom Loop",
                  "short": "Fear and focus can make the burn louder.",
                  "detail": "Stress does not mean reflux is imaginary. Stress can change sensitivity, breathing, tension, and perception of discomfort, making symptoms feel more intense or harder to ignore."
              }
          ],
          "interpretations": {
              "clinical": {
                  "label": "Strictly Medical",
                  "title": "Reflux Barrier & Acid Exposure Cascade",
                  "sections": [
                      {
                          "heading": "Stage 1 — Reflux Pressure",
                          "body": [
                              "Acid reflux happens when stomach contents move upward into the esophagus.",
                              "This can be influenced by meal size, timing, lying down after eating, abdominal pressure, trigger foods, hiatal hernia, pregnancy, smoking, weight changes, and some medications."
                          ]
                      },
                      {
                          "heading": "Stage 2 — Lower Esophageal Sphincter Function",
                          "body": [
                              "The lower esophageal sphincter is the valve-like barrier between the stomach and esophagus.",
                              "When it relaxes inappropriately, weakens, or is overwhelmed by pressure, reflux can occur."
                          ]
                      },
                      {
                          "heading": "Stage 3 — Esophageal Irritation",
                          "body": [
                              "Repeated acid exposure can irritate the esophagus and throat.",
                              "Symptoms may include heartburn, sour taste, regurgitation, cough, hoarseness, throat burning, nausea, or chest discomfort."
                          ]
                      },
                      {
                          "heading": "Stage 4 — Stress and Symptom Sensitivity",
                          "body": [
                              "Stress can amplify reflux symptoms by changing breathing, muscle tension, sleep, eating patterns, and nervous-system sensitivity.",
                              "That does not make reflux symbolic only. It means the body and stress system are rude enough to collaborate."
                          ]
                      }
                  ]
              },
              "witty": {
                  "label": "Comedic & Witty",
                  "title": "Gary and the Backwards Sewer System",
                  "paragraphs": [
                      "Your digestive system is now a poorly designed, underfunded sewer system in a town that keeps flushing things it should not.",
                      "Your stomach is the tank. Normally, flow goes downward. But two furious supervisors named Cortisol and Adrenaline keep hitting the backflow button because you never know when you might need to revisit something.",
                      "The lower esophageal sphincter is the valve at the top of the tank. It is supposed to close tightly. One-way flow only. But Gary the pump operator has not had a break since 2004.",
                      "Gary keeps leaving the valve ajar. The pressure rises. The acid backs up into the esophagus, which is not designed for this nonsense.",
                      "The control room has a sign that says DON'T PANIC in Comic Sans. There is a coffee mug that says WORLD'S OKAYEST PUMP OPERATOR. Gary is doing his best, which is upsetting, because his best is currently acid in your throat.",
                      "And you keep taking antacids. Antacids can lower the burn. They do not necessarily fix the pressure, the timing, the valve behavior, or the emotional habit of swallowing fire and calling it dinner."
                  ]
              },
              "brutal": {
                  "label": "Brutally Honest",
                  "title": "The Swallowed Fire Reality Check",
                  "paragraphs": [
                      "You do have a reflux problem. You may also have an I will just keep it down problem.",
                      "How many times have you felt heat rise in your chest, anger in your throat, and truth behind your teeth, then swallowed it like a shot of poison?",
                      "Every it is fine that was absolutely not fine has to go somewhere. Every unfinished argument. Every swallowed insult. Every truth that scared you.",
                      "Food can trigger reflux. Spicy food, late meals, chocolate, alcohol, coffee, stress eating, and lying down too soon can matter. But sometimes the burn also asks what you keep refusing to say.",
                      "Medication can matter. Lifestyle changes can matter. Medical care can matter. But if your whole life is one long performance of swallowing fire, do not act shocked when the fire keeps rising.",
                      "The next time the burn shows up, ask: what am I keeping down that wants to come up?",
                      "Speak it safely. Write it. Say it to the mirror. Stop making your esophagus hold a press conference for every sentence you buried.",
                      "Armor down or stay inflamed. Charming little bargain."
                  ]
              }
          },
          "influenceLayers": [
              {
                  "layer": 1,
                  "title": "Stomach Qi Rebellion",
                  "tag": "Middle Burner",
                  "paragraphs": [
                      "In Chinese medicine, Stomach Qi normally descends. Food, experience, and emotion are meant to move downward and onward.",
                      "Reflux symbolically mirrors a reversal: what should descend rises instead."
                  ]
              },
              {
                  "layer": 2,
                  "title": "Liver Fire Invading Stomach",
                  "tag": "Wood Over Earth",
                  "paragraphs": [
                      "The Liver is associated with smooth flow and anger. When anger is stuck or swallowed, the symbolic Liver pattern can press into the Stomach.",
                      "The result is fire moving upward: heat, pressure, irritation, and the feeling of words burning their way back up."
                  ]
              },
              {
                  "layer": 3,
                  "title": "Swallowed Fire Archetype",
                  "tag": "Shadow Voice",
                  "paragraphs": [
                      "The Speaker is the part that names what is wrong.",
                      "When that voice is suppressed long enough, the throat and chest become the symbolic chimney for fire that was never spoken."
                  ]
              },
              {
                  "layer": 4,
                  "title": "Throat Gate",
                  "tag": "Expression",
                  "paragraphs": [
                      "The symptom may ask what truth is trying to rise.",
                      "The body may be saying: this cannot stay down forever."
                  ]
              },
              {
                  "layer": 5,
                  "title": "Descending the Fire",
                  "tag": "Reset Practice",
                  "paragraphs": [
                      "The goal is downward settling: upright posture, slower exhale, less pressure, and honest naming.",
                      "Do not use emotional reflection as a substitute for reflux care, medication guidance, or evaluation of concerning symptoms."
                  ]
              }
          ],
          "reset": {
              "title": "Stomach Qi Descending & Liver Fire Cooling",
              "modality": "Autonomic Downregulation",
              "steps": [
                  "Sit upright. Place one hand on the sternum and one hand on the lower belly.",
                  "Inhale through the nose for 4 seconds, imagining cool silver light moving from throat to stomach.",
                  "Exhale through the mouth for 8 seconds, imagining heat leaving through the hands.",
                  "On each exhale, whisper: I do not have to swallow what burns me. I release what I should have said.",
                  "Continue for 2 minutes. Stay upright afterward."
              ]
          },
          "naturalSupport": {
              "title": "Supportive Care",
              "disclaimer": "Supportive care is not a cure. Persistent or concerning reflux symptoms need medical evaluation.",
              "items": [
                  {
                      "label": "Meal timing",
                      "detail": "Avoid lying down soon after eating; many people do better staying upright after meals."
                  },
                  {
                      "label": "Smaller meals",
                      "detail": "Large meals can increase reflux pressure."
                  },
                  {
                      "label": "Trigger tracking",
                      "detail": "Track foods, timing, alcohol, caffeine, stress, sleep, and symptoms."
                  },
                  {
                      "label": "Sleep position",
                      "detail": "Some people use head-of-bed elevation or left-side sleeping for nighttime reflux support."
                  }
              ],
              "avoid": [
                  "Do not ignore chest pain, trouble swallowing, vomiting blood, black stool, or unexplained weight loss.",
                  "Do not stop prescribed reflux medication without medical guidance."
              ]
          },
          "brutalActions": [
