                  "Poor Absorption",
                  "Fluid Loss"
              ],
              "tags": [
                  "#rapid transit",
                  "#urgency",
                  "#containment"
              ],
              "safetyPreview": "Dehydration, blood, fever, severe pain, persistent diarrhea, recent antibiotics, travel exposure, pregnancy, or high-risk health status needs medical evaluation."
          },
          "biologyPathway": [
              {
                  "title": "Transit Speeds Up",
                  "short": "The gut moves too quickly.",
                  "detail": "Diarrhea can happen when stool moves through the intestines too quickly for water to be absorbed properly."
              },
              {
                  "title": "Fluid Stays in the Stool",
                  "short": "Water is not reclaimed.",
                  "detail": "Infections, irritation, inflammation, certain foods, medications, anxiety, and stress can all alter fluid handling in the gut."
              },
              {
                  "title": "Enteric Alarm",
                  "short": "The gut's nerve network gets reactive.",
                  "detail": "The enteric nervous system coordinates motility and secretion. When irritated or stressed, it may push contents through with rude, unnecessary urgency."
              },
              {
                  "title": "Dehydration Risk",
                  "short": "Fluid loss can become the danger.",
                  "detail": "The symptom may be embarrassing, but the real risk is dehydration, electrolyte imbalance, or missing a more serious cause."
              }
          ],
          "interpretations": {
              "clinical": {
                  "label": "Strictly Medical",
                  "title": "Rapid Transit & Fluid Loss Cascade",
                  "sections": [
                      {
                          "heading": "Stage 1 — Rapid Transit",
                          "body": [
                              "Diarrhea is medically a digestive symptom. It can happen when stool moves through the intestines too quickly or when excess fluid remains in the stool.",
                              "Possible causes include viral or bacterial infection, food poisoning, food intolerance, medication effects, stress, anxiety, IBS, inflammatory bowel disease, gallbladder issues, or other medical causes."
                          ]
                      },
                      {
                          "heading": "Stage 2 — Enteric Nervous System Activation",
                          "body": [
                              "The gut has its own nerve network, the enteric nervous system. It helps regulate motility, secretion, and sensitivity.",
                              "Stress does not make diarrhea fake. Stress can change gut movement, urgency, sensitivity, and how quickly the system tries to clear itself."
                          ]
                      },
                      {
                          "heading": "Stage 3 — Water Absorption Failure",
                          "body": [
                              "When transit is too fast, the colon has less time to absorb water.",
                              "The result can be loose stool, urgency, cramping, bloating, and that deeply undignified sprint toward porcelain civilization."
                          ]
                      },
                      {
                          "heading": "Stage 4 — Escalation Check",
                          "body": [
                              "The biggest concern is dehydration or a serious underlying cause.",
                              "Blood, black stool, fever, severe abdominal pain, repeated vomiting, signs of dehydration, diarrhea after antibiotics, recent travel, pregnancy, immunocompromised status, or symptoms lasting more than a couple days should be taken seriously."
                          ]
                      }
                  ]
              },
              "witty": {
                  "label": "Comedic & Witty",
                  "title": "The Firefighter With Too Many False Alarms",
                  "paragraphs": [
                      "Your colon is now a chronically overworked, underpaid firefighter who has been responding to false alarms for years.",
                      "The siren is always going off. The hose is always leaking. The fire is either a real digestive issue or your own panic wearing a tiny firefighter helmet.",
                      "Normally, the firefighter responds with appropriate urgency. But stress hormones named Cortisol and Adrenaline keep calling in every emotion as a five-alarm fire.",
                      "A thought? Emergency. A deadline? Emergency. A suspicious taco? Emergency with sirens.",
                      "The firefighter stops inspecting the scene and just blasts everything out. That is diarrhea: evacuate first, process later.",
                      "The fire station poster says EVACUATE FIRST. PROCESS LATER. Someone wrote STOP SENDING FALSE ALARMS underneath. Nobody listened, because apparently the management committee is made of caffeine and unresolved dread."
                  ]
              },
              "brutal": {
                  "label": "Brutally Honest",
                  "title": "The Overwhelm Reality Check",
                  "paragraphs": [
                      "You do have a diarrhea problem. You may also have an everything is urgent problem.",
                      "Your body may be saying: I cannot hold this, process this, contain this, and pretend I am fine at the same time.",
                      "You have been pushing through, handling everything, absorbing chaos, and calling it normal because apparently humans think suffering quietly is a personality trait.",
                      "Food, infection, medication, inflammation, and medical issues absolutely matter. Do not turn every bowel movement into a childhood analysis seminar.",
                      "But if diarrhea shows up every time life becomes too much, ask the useful question: what am I trying to evacuate before I have actually processed it?",
                      "You may need fluids. You may need rest. You may need medical care. You may also need to stop living like every inconvenience is a burning building.",
                      "Ask for help before your body starts filing emergency reports through your colon.",
                      "Lower the emergency setting or keep evacuating every signal like a disaster drill."
                  ]
              }
          },
          "influenceLayers": [
              {
                  "layer": 1,
                  "title": "Spleen Containment",
                  "tag": "Earth Element",
                  "paragraphs": [
                      "In Chinese medicine, the Spleen is associated with processing, transforming, and containing.",
                      "Symbolically, diarrhea can mirror a system that cannot hold long enough to process."
                  ]
              },
              {
                  "layer": 2,
                  "title": "Kidney Fear & Collapse",
                  "tag": "Water Element",
                  "paragraphs": [
                      "The Kidney pattern relates to fear, reserves, and the deep sense of safety.",
                      "When safety feels gone, the symbolic body may stop containing and start evacuating."
                  ]
              },
              {
                  "layer": 3,
                  "title": "The Leaky Vessel Archetype",
                  "tag": "Shadow Container",
                  "paragraphs": [
                      "The Container is the part that can hold experience without cracking.",
                      "When overwhelmed, the vessel leaks. The body says: this is too much to hold."
                  ]
              },
              {
                  "layer": 4,
                  "title": "Urgency Pattern",
                  "tag": "Somatic Alarm",
                  "paragraphs": [
                      "This symptom can ask where life has become all urgency and no digestion.",
                      "The body may be trying to clear something before it knows what it is."
                  ]
              },
              {
                  "layer": 5,
                  "title": "Containment Reset",
                  "tag": "Grounding Practice",
                  "paragraphs": [
                      "The symbolic goal is not clenching harder. It is safe containment.",
                      "Breath, warmth, fluids, and support tell the body it does not have to evacuate every signal immediately."
                  ]
              }
          ],
          "reset": {
              "title": "Spleen Qi Containing & Kidney Anchoring",
              "modality": "Autonomic Downregulation",
              "steps": [
                  "Sit or lie down and place both hands on the lower belly.",
                  "Inhale through the nose for 4 seconds, imagining warmth spreading through the abdomen.",
                  "Exhale through the mouth for 8 seconds, imagining heaviness draining down through the feet.",
                  "On each exhale, whisper: I am safe. I can hold what is mine. I release what I do not need to hold.",
                  "Continue for 2 minutes. Prioritize fluids and medical care if red flags are present."
              ]
          },
          "naturalSupport": {
              "title": "Supportive Care",
              "disclaimer": "Supportive care is not a cure. Diarrhea can become dangerous through dehydration or serious underlying causes.",
              "items": [
                  {
                      "label": "Fluids",
                      "detail": "Use small frequent sips of water or oral rehydration/electrolyte fluids."
                  },
                  {
                      "label": "Rest",
                      "detail": "Give the gut and nervous system a lower-demand environment instead of pretending you are a productivity machine with plumbing."
                  },
                  {
                      "label": "Bland foods",
                      "detail": "Simple tolerated foods may help while symptoms settle."
                  },
                  {
                      "label": "Trigger tracking",
                      "detail": "Track meals, travel, sick contacts, medications, stress, and timing."
                  }
              ],
              "avoid": [
                  "Do not ignore dehydration, blood, fever, severe pain, persistent diarrhea, or diarrhea after antibiotics.",
                  "Do not use anti-diarrheal medication when there is fever, bloody stool, or suspected serious infection unless medically advised."
              ]
          },
          "brutalActions": [
              "Hydrate first. Philosophy second.",
              "Ask: what feels too urgent to process?",
              "Lower demand on your system for a few hours.",
              "Get care for dehydration, blood, fever, severe pain, recent antibiotics, travel illness, pregnancy, or persistent symptoms."
          ]
      },
      "tones": {
          "clinical": {
              "mechanism": "Diarrhea can involve rapid intestinal transit, increased fluid in the stool, infection, food intolerance, inflammation, medication effects, anxiety, stress, or enteric nervous system dysregulation.",
              "protocol": [
                  "Prioritize fluids and electrolytes.",
                  "Track food, medication, travel, stress, and timing.",
                  "Seek care for dehydration, blood, fever, severe pain, persistent symptoms, recent antibiotics, pregnancy, or high-risk health status."
              ],
              "citations": [
                  "Educational reflection only; not a substitute for diagnosis or medical care."
              ]
          },
          "witty": {
              "metaphorTitle": "The Firefighter With Too Many False Alarms",
              "metaphorText": "Your colon is an exhausted firefighter who keeps blasting the hose because every signal is being reported as a five-alarm fire.",
              "wittyAdvice": "Turn off the siren, hydrate, and stop making your colon respond to emails like they are burning buildings."
          },
          "brutal": {
              "realityCheck": "You do have a diarrhea problem. You may also have an everything is urgent problem.",
              "protocolTitle": "STOP THE FALSE ALARM",
              "protocolSteps": [
                  "Hydrate first.",
                  "Name what feels urgent.",
                  "Reduce demand on your system.",
                  "Get care for red flags or persistent symptoms."
              ]
          }
      }
  },
  {
      "id": "eye-farsighted",
      "name": "Eye (Farsighted)",
      "category": "Head & Neck",
      "emotionalRoot": "Future focus, missing the near, reaching toward the horizon, and difficulty seeing what is right in front of you.",
      "metaphor": "Your eyes are a telescope pointed at the horizon while the present sits at your feet holding a little sign.",
      "physiologicalDescription": "Farsightedness/hyperopia is a refractive error where light focuses behind the retina, often due to eye shape or corneal curvature. It can cause near blur, eyestrain, headaches, squinting, and difficulty with close work.",
      "sarcasticAdvice": "Do not blame moral failure for blurry near vision. Eyeballs are shaped objects, unfortunately not motivational software.",
      "mindfulnessPrompts": [
          "What is close that I am missing?",
          "What needs an eye exam?",
          "Where am I reaching past the present?",
          "What detail matters now?"
      ],
      "physicalTherapyTip": "Track near blur, headaches, squinting, eye strain, reading difficulty, prescription changes, sudden vision changes, eye pain, flashes/floaters, or vision loss.",
      "medical_safety": {
          "critical_alerts": [
              "Sudden vision loss or sudden vision change",
              "Eye pain, severe redness, flashes, floaters, curtain/shadow vision loss",
              "Eye trauma, chemical exposure, severe headache with vision symptoms",
              "New double vision or neurologic symptoms"
          ],
          "seek_immediate_care_if": [
              "Sudden vision change/loss, eye pain, flashes/floaters, trauma, chemical exposure, or neurologic symptoms occur"
          ],
          "schedule_care_if": [
              "Near blur, headaches, squinting, reading difficulty, or prescription changes persist"
          ],
          "self_care_allowed_if": "Good lighting, breaks, and prescribed correction can support known refractive error.",
          "do_not_ignore": "Sudden eye symptoms can be urgent.",
          "disclaimer": "This app is for education and self-reflection only. It does not diagnose, treat, prevent, or cure disease."
      },
      "tags": [
