                  "title": "Reflux Barrier & Acid Exposure Cascade",
                  "sections": [
                      {
                          "heading": "Stage 1 — Reflux Pressure",
                          "body": [
                              "Heartburn is medically a reflux symptom. It usually happens when stomach contents move upward into the esophagus.",
                              "Meal size, late eating, lying down after meals, abdominal pressure, trigger foods, smoking, alcohol, medications, pregnancy, and hiatal hernia can contribute."
                          ]
                      },
                      {
                          "heading": "Stage 2 — Lower Esophageal Sphincter Function",
                          "body": [
                              "The lower esophageal sphincter is the valve-like barrier between the stomach and esophagus.",
                              "When it relaxes inappropriately, weakens, or is overwhelmed by pressure, reflux can happen."
                          ]
                      },
                      {
                          "heading": "Stage 3 — Esophageal Irritation",
                          "body": [
                              "The esophagus is not designed for repeated acid exposure.",
                              "Symptoms can include burning, sour taste, regurgitation, cough, hoarseness, nausea, throat irritation, or chest discomfort."
                          ]
                      },
                      {
                          "heading": "Stage 4 — Escalation Check",
                          "body": [
                              "Chest pain should not automatically be assumed to be heartburn.",
                              "Trouble swallowing, vomiting blood, black stool, unexplained weight loss, persistent vomiting, severe symptoms, or ongoing reflux should be medically evaluated."
