                  "title": "Spinal Curve",
                  "short": "The spine curves side-to-side.",
                  "detail": "Scoliosis involves lateral curvature and often rotation, measured clinically and radiographically."
              },
              {
                  "title": "Growth and Progression",
                  "short": "Age and growth matter.",
                  "detail": "Adolescent curves may progress during growth; adult curves can be degenerative or related to prior curves."
              },
              {
                  "title": "Symptoms",
                  "short": "Pain and asymmetry vary.",
                  "detail": "Some people have visible asymmetry without pain; others develop back pain, imbalance, or in severe cases breathing limits."
              },
              {
                  "title": "Treatment Paths",
                  "short": "Observation, PT, bracing, or surgery.",
                  "detail": "Care depends on curve size, age, progression, symptoms, and risk. Naturally, the spine made it complicated."
              }
          ],
          "interpretations": {
              "clinical": {
                  "label": "Strictly Medical",
                  "title": "Spinal Curve, Rotation & Progression Monitoring",
                  "sections": [
                      {
                          "heading": "Stage 1 — Structural Curve",
                          "body": [
                              "Scoliosis is a structural side-to-side curve, often with rotation.",
                              "It is not just bad posture, though posture can influence comfort."
                          ]
                      },
                      {
                          "heading": "Stage 2 — Measurement",
                          "body": [
                              "Curves are commonly tracked with imaging and measurements like Cobb angle.",
                              "Progression risk depends on growth, curve size, type, and age."
                          ]
                      },
                      {
                          "heading": "Stage 3 — Treatment Options",
                          "body": [
                              "Options can include observation, scoliosis-specific physical therapy, bracing during growth, pain management, or surgery for severe/progressive cases.",
                              "The spine, being a diva, prefers individualized engineering."
                          ]
                      },
                      {
                          "heading": "Stage 4 — Safety Check",
                          "body": [
                              "Seek care for progressive curve, severe pain, neurologic symptoms, weakness/numbness, breathing trouble, or bowel/bladder changes.",
                              "A leaning tower still deserves an inspection."
                          ]
                      }
                  ]
              },
              "witty": {
                  "label": "Comedic & Witty",
                  "title": "The Leaning Tower",
                  "paragraphs": [
                      "Your spine is a leaning tower with one side carrying more load than the other.",
                      "The foundation may be fine, or it may need serious engineering review.",
                      "The builders keep saying we'll straighten it later, which is a bold management plan for architecture.",
                      "Sometimes it needs monitoring. Sometimes bracing. Sometimes PT. Sometimes surgery.",
                      "Balance is not pretending the curve is fake. Balance is supporting the structure that exists.",
                      "Balance the tower support or keep asking a leaning structure to pretend gravity is optional. Your choice."
                  ]
              },
              "brutal": {
                  "label": "Brutally Honest",
                  "title": "The Uneven Load Reality Check",
                  "paragraphs": [
                      "You may have scoliosis. You may also have an uneven-load pattern.",
                      "Medical first: scoliosis is structural and needs appropriate monitoring, especially with progression, pain, growth, neurologic signs, or breathing symptoms.",
                      "Symbolically, ask where life became one-sided.",
                      "What burden keeps pulling you off center?",
                      "You can seek center without denying the curve.",
                      "Balance the tower support or keep asking a leaning structure to pretend gravity is optional. Your choice."
                  ]
              }
          },
          "influenceLayers": [
              {
                  "layer": 1,
                  "title": "Central Axis",
                  "tag": "Spine",
                  "paragraphs": [
                      "The spine is the body's central pillar.",
                      "Scoliosis symbolically asks where the axis has been pulled."
                  ]
              },
              {
                  "layer": 2,
                  "title": "Uneven Load",
                  "tag": "Asymmetry",
                  "paragraphs": [
                      "One-sided burden becomes the symbolic language.",
                      "Structural care still matters more than poetic symmetry."
                  ]
              },
              {
                  "layer": 3,
                  "title": "Leaning Tower",
                  "tag": "Engineering",
                  "paragraphs": [
                      "The tower needs support, not shame.",
                      "Measurement beats guessing. Annoying, but true."
                  ]
              },
              {
                  "layer": 4,
                  "title": "Center Finder",
                  "tag": "Balance",
                  "paragraphs": [
